and probably this isnt like... erasing it, but you can basically change the ending to your trauma. imagine yourself braver or imagine yourself being rescued. its probably more complicated than that, but thats the basic idea
theres this idea that the brain cannot separate dreams, memories, and thoughts from each other. false memories are usually harmful, but in some cases you can literally change your trauma.
it is kind of a helpful exercise... just imagining, for example, how you would seek comfort and guidance and just... give it to yourself. ESPECIALLY for ppl w cptsd from child abuse and/or bullying.

I even see shit like this with fics and hcs that try to be woke but just end up homophobic, racist, transphobic, etc. because they didn't do proper research or even just. Have someone of one of those groups proofread it. It's literally so easy...

I just get annoyed when people try to say shit like "lesbians disagree with this!" Or "ADHDers all do this!". You may represent some, but you silence and shame all others. ESPECIALLY if you say that without being part of the group.

Harmful things to say include: "this disorder does this!" Or "this medication does this!" Or even "people of this group feel this way!" Unless you're literally speaking about symptoms, you can't just. Be so egotistical to assume your experience represents the entire group.

There are ways to advocate for things other than giving your opinions, for ex, sharing peer reviewed studies or starting with "this is my experience with x". But your experiences are not universal, and you have a duty to properly represent yourself.

I think when you have a platform it's important to be open about your experiences with invisible illnesses or lgbt identities. But. It's really insensitive to give out professional advice about those things. If you want to share a study, ok, but otherwise you aren't a doctor...
